## Implementation Characteristics

### 1. BillingWorkbench becomes the new presentation shell

The billing surface now renders through a dedicated `BillingWorkbench` widget instead of depending directly on the former simple table widget.

That workbench is responsible only for presentation concerns:

- local page state
- visible-range slicing
- layout rhythm
- desktop-oriented toolbar/summary/footer structure
- reuse of the preexisting download action flow

### 2. Pagination remains local and safe

The controller and backend communication remain unchanged.

The workbench consumes the same row list already produced by `BillingController.buildTableRows(...)` and performs only local slicing in memory.

That means:

- no contract changes
- no request changes
- no backend coupling increase
- no business-rule expansion

### 3. Toolbar baseline is introduced

A toolbar now provides:

- contextual title
- current total-record count
- rows-per-page selector
- explicit refresh action

This turns the billing surface into an operational workbench without yet forcing filtering or sorting semantics into the same subphase.

### 4. Summary strip is introduced

A dedicated summary block now exposes:

- visible range
- current page / total pages
- current billing collection label

This improves orientation, especially when the billing dataset grows.

### 5. Table structure becomes modular

The old single-file table logic is replaced by a modular structure with:

- column contract model
- header widget
- row widget
- table shell
- pagination footer

This makes later iterations safer because the workbench can now evolve without reopening the whole billing feature in a monolithic way.

### 6. Legacy compatibility remains available

`BillingDocumentsTable` is preserved as a compatibility wrapper that now delegates to the new workbench shell.

That means the repository keeps a safer migration boundary while the canonical billing caller already uses the new workbench directly.

## Validation

Phase 14.2.1 is correctly represented only if the current ZIP now supports all of the following:

- `BillingWidget` uses a workbench-oriented presentation surface
- pagination is handled locally in the billing presentation layer
- rows-per-page can be changed without touching backend contracts
- billing still supports downloading a document from each visible row
- the workbench adapts by constraints rather than platform branching
- the previous `BillingDocumentsTable` path remains usable as a compatibility wrapper

The current ZIP supports that reading.

## Risks

Primary controlled risks in this subphase were:

- introducing too much behavior into presentation state
- accidentally changing the billing download contract
- making the workbench assume full-screen instead of an embedded window environment
- adding sorting/filtering/grouping too early and overloading the phase

The implementation avoids those risks by:

- keeping pagination local and presentation-only
- preserving the row download action contract
- keeping the workbench embedded-friendly
- limiting this subphase to toolbar + summary + table + pagination baseline

## Conclusion

Phase 14.2.1 completes the first real billing workbench baseline.

The billing feature no longer presents its documents through a temporary-feeling embedded table alone.
It now exposes a structured workbench surface with:

- toolbar
- summary
- paginated table rhythm
- footer navigation
- preserved download behavior

This leaves the project in a stronger position for the next billing modernization steps without reopening architecture, runtime, business logic, or backend contracts.
